</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">B. D. Dell 8216</emphasis>
(G, MO).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">
<pageBreakToken pageId="8" pageNumber="49" start="start">Note</pageBreakToken>
:
</emphasis>
Tepals orange to red, in 3 whorls. Growing in young stems of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Gastrolobium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Gastrolobium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Oxylobium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Fabales" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Oxylobium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in Western Australia (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Geographic distribution of Apodanthaceae based on label information from 785 herbarium collections." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10621" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Figs 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Phylogenetic relationships among the hosts of Apodanthaceae (legume relationships from Wojciechowski et al. 2006) and among the species of Apodanthaceae (from Bellot and Renner in review). Identical colors link parasite species and their host (s) and are also used in Figure 2. Dashed lines represent associations with rarely reported hosts; hosts in bold are the most common ones." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10622" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">3</figureCitation>
, see 
<bibRefCitation author="Thiele, KR" journalOrPublisher="Nuytsia" pageId="12" pageNumber="53" pagination="273 - 284" refId="B16" refString="Thiele, KR, Wylie, SJ, Maccarone, L, Hollick, P, McComb, JA, 2008. Pilostyles coccoidea (Apodanthaceae), a new species from Western Australia described from morphological and molecular evidence. Nuytsia 18: 273 - 284" title="Pilostyles coccoidea (Apodanthaceae), a new species from Western Australia described from morphological and molecular evidence." volume="18" year="2008">Thiele et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
for pictures of flowers).
</paragraph>
